Bombs.

A bomb is a placed explosive that sits on a tile, counts down a fuse, and then detonates — damaging whoever or whatever is standing on that tile when it goes off. There are two kinds, built from two separate builder entries but documented together here because they work almost identically: the plain bomb, a quiet charge that simply goes off when its timer runs out, and the time bomb, the same charge fitted with an audible countdown that ticks faster and faster as it's about to blow. Bomb zones, covered at the end of this topic, turn an area into a bombardment that rains bombs while the player is inside it.

How a bomb works.

A bomb occupies a single tile and carries a fuse and a damage value. When it's placed, an incoming cue plays — the sound of the bomb dropping in. Once its fuse runs out it detonates: it plays its blast sound and damages whatever shares its tile at that instant.

If it's the player, they take the damage, reduced by their defence. A raised shield soaks the hit instead of the player's health.
If it's an enemy or a destroyable map object — a wall, door, sign, clock, calendar, item, spike, or a parked vehicle — that target takes the damage.

If the tile is empty when the fuse runs out, the bomb goes off harmlessly.

A bomb detonates once and is then gone. Because it only affects its own tile, a bomb is a precise trap: it threatens the exact spot you place it on, not a blast radius around it.

The time bomb.

A time bomb behaves exactly like a bomb — single tile, a fuse, damage to whoever is on the tile when it blows, reduced by defence and absorbed by a shield — with one addition: an accelerating tick. When it's placed a drop cue plays, and then it begins ticking, slowly at first and speeding up steadily as the fuse runs down, until it's a rapid beeping in the moment before it detonates. This gives the player both a warning that a bomb is present and a growing sense of how close it is to going off, so they can clear the tile in time.

Use a plain bomb for a silent trap the player can't hear coming, and a time bomb when you want to telegraph the danger and build tension as it counts down.

Bomb fields.

Both the bomb and the time bomb forms take the following:

Coordinates. An x and y (and z on 3d maps) — the tile the bomb sits on and detonates on.

Attack. How much damage the bomb deals to whatever is on its tile when it goes off, reduced by the target's defence.

Speed. The fuse, in milliseconds — how long after placement the bomb detonates.

Bomb sound (a folder name from the bomb sounds list, or none). The audio theme. A plain bomb's bundle supplies a fall clip (the incoming drop) and a land clip (the blast). A time bomb's bundle adds a drop clip, a tick clip (the accelerating countdown), and a hit clip alongside the blast. Pick none for a silent bomb.

Looping sound (time bomb only). Off by default, which gives the familiar countdown — the tick speeds up steadily as the fuse runs down. Turn it on to play the tick at a steady pace instead, without accelerating. This is handy when your tick clip is long, since the accelerating countdown keeps restarting the clip and would cut a long one short, while the looping option lets it play through cleanly. Either way the speed still decides when the bomb detonates; this only changes how the tick sounds while it waits.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

In the bomb form, while the bomb sound list is focused, press space to hear the blast (land) clip and hold control and press L to hear the incoming (fall) clip. In the time bomb form, press space to hear the blast clip and hold control and press L to hear the tick clip.

Bomb zones.

A bomb zone is a rectangular area that bombards the player the whole time they stand inside it. Every spawn time, it drops a bomb at a random tile within its bounds, so the longer the player lingers in the zone the more bombs fall around them. The bombs a zone drops scale their damage to the player's experience and use a short random fuse, so a bomb zone is a pressure trap — a field the player has to cross quickly rather than wait in.

The bomb zone form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x, and a y (a minimum and maximum y on topdown and 3d maps), and a z on 3d maps — the rectangle bombs fall within, which is also the area the player must be standing in for the bombardment to fire.

Spawn time. Milliseconds between drops while the player is inside.

Bomb sound (a folder name from the bomb sounds list, or none). The theme for the bombs the zone drops.

Unlike a placed bomb, a bomb zone takes no damage value — the bombs it drops set their own damage from the player's level. While the bomb sound list is focused, press space to hear a blast clip and hold control and press L to hear an incoming clip.

Authoring bombs by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly:

A bomb is: bomb x y damage speed bombtype. On 3d maps a z follows y: bomb x y z damage speed bombtype.

A time bomb is: time_bomb x y damage speed timebombtype looping. On 3d maps a z follows y: time_bomb x y z damage speed timebombtype looping. The looping value is true or false — true plays the tick steadily, false gives the accelerating countdown.

A bomb zone is: bomb_zone minx maxx y spawntime bombtype on 2d maps, bomb_zone minx maxx miny maxy spawntime bombtype on topdown maps, and bomb_zone minx maxx miny maxy z spawntime bombtype on 3d maps.

The damage, speed, and spawn time are whole numbers, and every bomb sound must match a bomb sounds folder name (or, for a time bomb, a time bomb sounds folder name), or the word none.
